JOHANNESBURG – South Africa’s labour force has been ranked as the fifth hardest-working in the world. A study by the Organisation for Economic Co-operation Development shows that nearly 12 percent of South Africans spend more than 60 hours-a-week on the job. READ: Who are the world's happiest people? The hardest workers are found in the mining and retail sectors. Labourers in more affluent provinces work less than their counterparts in poorer areas. The Eastern Cape, however, has the lowest working hours. This is due to the low number of permanent employees. eNCA